Joseph-&quot;TeacherGuy&quot;,<br><br>
Please do not apologize for a lengthy expression of your feelings and ideas. I, for one, enjoy reading every word.<br><br>
Jonathan Shay in &quot;Achilles in Vietnam&quot; calls the killing &quot;frenzy&quot; a berserk state. There is substantial evidence, as Gerry implies, that there is a long historical thread to this combat phenomenon. While acts of violence performed on civilians by berserk soldiers are considered atrocities, there seems to have been an opinion by some in Vietnam that the beserk state of mind was desireable when engaged in combat. <br><br>
Therein lies a double standard. There may be no cognitive differentiation within the berserk mind.<br><br>
Though I do not feel I was ever in what is considered a classic berserk state of mind during my experiences in the Vietnam War, there are very dark feelings residing in places within my mind with which I have yet to come to grips. I have an empathy for those caught in the grip of derision over the fate of civilians. I also grieve for those innocently harmed.<br><br>
It is an issue that really continues to bother me. I feel there may be no real answer. It seems, however, to be a price one pays for being human.
